The '''Ghana national football team''' represents [[Ghana]] in men's international [[Association football|football]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Black Stars|url=https://www.ghanafa.org/category/black-stars|work=Ghana Football Association|language=en|access-date=22 May 2020|archive-date=23 May 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200523044246/https://www.ghanafa.org/category/black-stars|url-status=live}}</ref> The team is named the '''Black Stars''' after the [[Black Star of Africa]] in the [[flag of Ghana]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Ghana Flag Ghana High Commission |url=https://www.ghanahighcommissionuk.com/ghanaflag.aspx |access-date=2023-07-19 |website=Brazil Consulate}}</ref> It is governed by the [[Ghana Football Association]], the governing body for [[football in Ghana]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Ghana Football Association, Biography | url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/person/Ghana-Football-Association-3586 }}</ref> Prior to 1957, it played as the [[Gold Coast (British colony)|Gold Coast]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Black Stars, Biography | url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/person/Black-Stars-3622 }}</ref>

Ghana qualified for the [[FIFA World Cup]] for the first time in [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2021-09-07 |title=How Ghana has started every World Cup qualifying campaign since Germany 2006 run |url=https://citisportsonline.com/2021/09/07/how-ghana-have-started-every-world-cup-qualifying-campaign-since-germany-2006-run/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230616201334/https://citisportsonline.com/2021/09/07/how-ghana-have-started-every-world-cup-qualifying-campaign-since-germany-2006-run/ |archive-date=16 June 2023 |access-date=2023-06-16 |website=Citi Sports Online |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-05-18 |title='I knew I would score against Czech Republic' – Asamoah Gyan on 2006 World Cup goal |url=https://citisportsonline.com/2022/05/18/i-knew-i-would-score-against-czech-republic-asamoah-gyan-on-2006-world-cup-goal/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230616201334/https://citisportsonline.com/2022/05/18/i-knew-i-would-score-against-czech-republic-asamoah-gyan-on-2006-world-cup-goal/ |archive-date=16 June 2023 |access-date=2023-06-16 |website=Citi Sports Online |language=en-US}}</ref> The team has won the [[Africa Cup of Nations]] four times ([[1963 African Cup of Nations|1963]], [[1965 African Cup of Nations|1965]], [[1978 African Cup of Nations|1978]], and [[1982 African Cup of Nations|1982]]), while finishing as runners-up five times ([[1968 African Cup of Nations|1968]], [[1970 African Cup of Nations|1970]], [[1992 African Cup of Nations|1992]], [[2010 Africa Cup of Nations|2010]], and [[2015 Africa Cup of Nations|2015]]).<ref>{{cite web | url=https://teamghanaeu.com/our-history/ | title=Our History }}</ref> They have also qualified for the [[African Nations Championship|CHAN]] four times, finishing as runners-up twice ([[2009 African Nations Championship|2009]] and [[2014 African Nations Championship|2014]]).<ref>{{cite news | date=16 January 2004 | url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/africa/3396199.stm | title=African Football: The early years | work=BBC | access-date=16 January 2004 | archive-date=24 January 2004 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040124113449/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/africa/3396199.stm | url-status=live }}</ref>

In 2009, Ghana achieved a historic milestone by becoming the first African nation to win the FIFA U-20 World Cup, defeating Brazil in the final in Egypt.<ref>{{cite web |title=Every FIFA U-20 World Cup final – Ghana champions 2009 |url=https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/u20worldcup/chile-2025/articles/every-u-20-world-cup-winner-argentina-brazil-france-messi-maradona |website=FIFA.com |access-date=15 January 2026}}</ref>

As at November 20, 2025, Ghana ranked 72nd in the world and 17th among African football nations.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-11-19 |title=Ghana's Black Stars climb up in FIFA Rankings despite recent losses to Japan & South Korea - Citi Sports Online |url=https://citisportsonline.com/2025/11/ghanas-black-stars-climb-up-in-fifa-rankings-despite-recent-losses-to-japan-south-korea/ |access-date=2025-11-20 |language=en-US}}</ref>

==History==
On 19 August 1962 at the [[Accra Sports Stadium]], Ghana hosted [[Real Madrid]], who were at the time [[List of Spanish football champions|Spanish champions]], drawing 3–3.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tablesm/madrid-friend6079.html |title=International Friendlies of Real Madrid CF 1960–1979 |website=[[RSSSF]] |access-date=29 May 2012 |archive-date=5 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230405060606/https://www.rsssf.org/tablesm/madrid-friend6079.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

[[Charles Kumi Gyamfi]] became coach in 1961, leading Ghana to successive [[African Cup of Nations]] titles, in [[1963 African Cup of Nations|1963]] and [[1965 African Cup of Nations|1965]]. The Black Stars achieved their record win, 13–2 away to [[Kenya national football team|Kenya]], in the latter.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://footballghana.com/relive-when-ghana-thrashed-kenya-13-2-kofi-pare-netted-6-times | title=Relive when Ghana thrashed Kenya 13-2, Kofi Pare netted 6 times | date=4 September 2018 }}</ref> They reached the final of the tournament in [[1968 African Cup of Nations|1968]] and [[1970 African Cup of Nations|1970]], losing 1–0 on both occasions, to [[DR Congo national football team|DR Congo]] and [[Sudan national football team|Sudan]] respectively.<ref name="podcasts.musixmatch.com">{{cite web | url=https://podcasts.musixmatch.com/search/topic/%C3%A9quipe_du_Ghana_de_football/Q172014 | title=Ghana men's national football team on Musixmatch Podcasts }}</ref> Their domination of the tournament earned them the nickname "the Black Stars of Africa" in the 1960s.<ref name="Ghana ready to fulfil their destiny">{{cite news | date=30 June 2013 | url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2010/jun/30/world-cup-2010-ghana-history | title=World Cup 2010: Ghana ready to fulfil their destiny | work=[[The Guardian]] | access-date=2 December 2013 | archive-date=3 December 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203122048/http://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2010/jun/30/world-cup-2010-ghana-history | url-status=live }}</ref>

Fortunes changed for the Black Stars however, after they failed to qualify for three successive AFCON's in the 1970s.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-40030710 |title=The Stanley Matthews football revolution made in Ghana |last=Anthony |first=Scott |date=26 May 2017 |website=[[bbc.co.uk]] |access-date=26 May 2017 |archive-date=19 November 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211119163458/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-40030710 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the early 1980s, however, with emerging talents such as [[Abedi Pele]], the Black Stars defeated [[1982 African Cup of Nations|1982 AFCON]] hosts [[Libya national football team|Libya]] in the [[1982 African Cup of Nations final|final]] to win their fourth and to date, last continental title.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pulse.com.gh/sports/today-in-history-ghana-beat-hosts-libya-to-win-afcon-1982-id4823896.html |title=Today in history - Ghana beat hosts Libya to win AFCON 1982 |access-date=2017-08-22 |date=19 March 2016 |df=dmy |archive-date=26 June 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230626164755/https://www.pulse.com.gh/sports/today-in-history-ghana-beat-hosts-libya-to-win-afcon-1982-id4823896.html |url-status=dead }}</ref> Fortunes changed again however, as in the 1984 tournament, they were knocked out in the group stages, before failing to qualify for the 1986, 1988 and 1990 tournaments.<ref name="podcasts.musixmatch.com"/> In 1992, the Black Stars would finish runners-up to the [[Ivory Coast national football team|Ivory Coast]] in a penalty shootout after a goalless draw, which saw every player on the pitch take a penalty, in which they were beaten 11-10,<ref>{{cite web |title=Ghana v Ivory Coast, 26 January 1992 |url=https://www.11v11.com/matches/ghana-v-ivory-coast-26-january-1992-243413 |website=11v11.com}}</ref> with [[African Footballer of the Year]] Abedi Pele suspended for the final.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://aedkit.com/ghana-blackstars-the-past-present-future/ | title=Ghana Blackstars : The Past, Present & Future | date=24 January 2024 }}</ref>

Tensions among the squad led to the [[Parliament of Ghana|parliamentary]] and [[Government of Ghana|executive]] to intervene and settle issues between players Abedi Pele and [[Tony Yeboah]]. In the 1990s, this may have played some part in the failure of the team to build on the successes of the national underage teams. However, the generation of Black Stars players who went to the [[2001 FIFA World Youth Championship]] final became the "core" of the team at the [[2002 African Cup of Nations]], going undefeated for a year in 2005 and [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF)|qualifying for the final tournament]] of the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]]. The Black Stars started by succumbing to a [[2006 FIFA World Cup Group E#Italy vs Ghana|2–0 defeat]] to eventual champions [[Italy national football team|Italy]], and wins over [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]] ([[2006 FIFA World Cup Group E#Czech Republic vs Ghana|2–0]]) and the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] ([[2006 FIFA World Cup Group E|2–1]]). This saw them advance through to the second round, where they lost [[2006 FIFA World Cup knockout stage#Brazil vs Ghana|3–0]] to [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]].<ref name="2006 World Cup – Part 2">{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gh/news/4375/editorials/2013/04/17/3910705/where-is-ghanas-2006-world-cup-squad-part-2|title=Where is Ghana's 2006 World Cup squad&nbsp;– Part 2|author=Joshua Ansah|work=goal.com|date=13 April 2013|access-date=13 December 2013|archive-date=8 May 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130508121017/http://www.goal.com/en-gh/news/4375/editorials/2013/04/17/3910705/where-is-ghanas-2006-world-cup-squad-part-2|url-status=live}}</ref>

Under head coach [[Milovan Rajevac]], the Black Stars went on to secure a 100% win record in their [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF)|qualification campaign]], winning their group and becoming the first African team to qualify for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]]. In the final tournament, they were placed in Group D with [[Germany national football team|Germany]], [[Serbia national football team|Serbia]] and [[Australia men's national soccer team|Australia]], advancing to the round of 16 after finishing second in their group. They played the United States, winning 2–1 in extra time to become only the third African nation to reach the World Cup quarter-finals, before losing to [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] in a [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shootout]] in the quarter-finals, after Uruguayan forward [[Luis Suárez]] blocked a header with his hand in the penalty box in extra time and was sent off. [[Asamoah Gyan]] missed the penalty given for the handball, with the score 1–1. Ghana went on to lose the penalty shootout 4–2, twelve years before [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]] became the first African team to qualify for the semi-finals of the World Cup.<ref>{{cite news | date=2 July 2013 | url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/jul/02/uruguay-ghana-world-cup-report | title=World Cup 2010: Uruguay make Gyan and Ghana pay the penalty | author=Paul Wilson | work=[[The Guardian]] | access-date=13 December 2013 | archive-date=9 June 2014 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140609074520/http://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/jul/02/uruguay-ghana-world-cup-report | url-status=live }}</ref>

In 2013, Ghana became the first team to reach four consecutive African Cup of Nations semi-finals twice, with the first occasion between 1963 and 1970.<ref>{{cite news |date=3 February 2013 |url=http://www.mtnfootball.com/africa/ghana/news/2013/feb/02-ghana-sets-nations-cup-record-with-cape-verde-win.html |title=Ghana equal Nations Cup record with Cape Verde win |work=mtnfootball.com |publisher=[[MTN Group]] |access-date=13 December 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213082703/http://www.mtnfootball.com/africa/ghana/news/2013/feb/02-ghana-sets-nations-cup-record-with-cape-verde-win.html |archive-date=13 December 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

The Black Stars won their [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification – CAF second round|second round]] group of [[2014 FIFA World Cup]] qualifying, and defeated [[Egypt national football team|Egypt]] 7–3 on aggregate in a two-legged play-off,<ref name="Black Stars win through">{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/match/124162/egypt-vs-ghana/report|title=Egypt 2–1 Ghana (Agg 3–7): Zaki and Gedo strike but Black Stars win through|work=goal.com|date=19 November 2013|access-date=13 December 2013|archive-date=13 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213231312/http://www.goal.com/en/match/124162/egypt-vs-ghana/report|url-status=live}}</ref> qualifying for the finals. They were drawn in [[2014 FIFA World Cup Group G|Group G]] for the finals, where they faced [[Germany national football team|Germany]], [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]], and the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]].<ref name="2014 FIFA World Cup Final Draw">{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/final-draw/draw.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131208080242/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/final-draw/draw.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=8 December 2013|title=2014 FIFA World Cup Final Draw|work=fifa.com|publisher=[[FIFA]]|date=6 December 2013|access-date=13 December 2013}}</ref> They exited in the group stage recording one draw against eventual champions Germany and two losses. However, they were the only team to not lose to Germany in the tournament, and the only team to hold onto a lead against the Germans at any point.

In the [[2015 Africa Cup of Nations]], they reached the final, being denied the title on penalties against [[Ivory Coast national football team|Ivory Coast]]. While their [[2017 Africa Cup of Nations]] campaign ended in a 4th-place finish, they finished behind [[Egypt national football team|Egypt]] and [[Uganda national football team|Uganda]] in their final group [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF)|qualifiers]] for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]]. At the [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations]], they were eliminated by [[Tunisia national football team|Tunisia]] in the round of 16. In 2021, manager Rajevac was brought back, but the Black Stars ended up failing to win a match at the [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations|AFCON]] where they lost 2–3 to debutants [[Comoros national football team|the Comoros]] after an [[André Ayew]] red card to finish bottom of their group, failing to progress beyond the group stage for the first time since 2006. They drew 0–0 in a match against [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]] and drew 1–1 in Nigeria to qualify for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] on [[away goals rule|away goals]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Nigeria vs. Ghana |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/629217 |website=ESPN |access-date=29 March 2022 |archive-date=30 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220330040340/https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/629217 |url-status=live }}</ref> During the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]], Ghana lost their first match against [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] 3–2. They earned their first and only victory in their second match against [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]] by the same scoreline. A victory against [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] was required for a spot in the round of 16 in a rematch of the 2010 quarter-final; Ghana instead lost 2–0 and thus finished bottom, while Uruguay was eliminated as well, as a result of South Korea upsetting Portugal.

Ghana failed to qualify for the [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations]], for the first time since 2004, as they finished bottom of the group below [[Angola national football team|Angola]], [[Sudan national football team|Sudan]], and [[Niger national football team|Niger]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/africa-cup-of-nations-qualification/2025/ghana-2025-africa-cup-of-nations-afcon-fail-qualify-jordan-ayew-angola_sto20054671/story.shtml|title=GHANA FAIL TO QUALIFY FOR 2025 AFRICA CUP OF NATIONS DESPITE JORDAN AYEW SCREAMER IN DRAW AGAINST ANGOLA|website=euronews.com|access-date=21 November 2024}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-11-16 |title=2025 AFCONQ: Black Stars were not good enough to qualify - Otto Addo - Adomonline.com |url=https://www.adomonline.com/2025-afconq-black-stars-were-not-good-enough-to-qualify-otto-addo/ |access-date=2024-11-26 |language=en-US}}</ref> However, they compensated by qualifying for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]], their fifth appearance, after gaining necessary wins against [[Mali national football team|Mali]] and [[Madagascar national football team|Madagascar]] despite inconsistency throughout the qualifiers.

== Culture ==
=== Kits and crest ===
{{Commons|Ghana national football team kits}}
[[File:Black Stars (Ghana national football team) Jersey 1970s—1980s.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Home shirt: 1970s–1980s]]

The official jersey colours for the Black Stars are white for home games and yellow for away games.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-11-15 |title=Puma unveils Ghana's new home and away jerseys |url=https://www.gbcghanaonline.com/sport/puma-ghana/2024/?amp=1 |access-date=2024-11-15 |website=GBC |language=en-US}}</ref>

Adopted following the independence of Ghana in 1957, the black star has been included in the Black Stars' kits. The ''Black Stars''' kits were sponsored by [[Puma SE]] from 2005, with the deal ending in 2014.<ref name="FA extends Puma deal to 2014">{{cite web|url=http://www.ghanafa.org/news/200801/2547.php|title=FA extends Puma deal to 2014|work=ghanafa.org|publisher=[[Ghana Football Association]] (GFA)|date=23 January 2008|access-date=7 February 2014|archive-date=22 February 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222140739/http://www.ghanafa.org/news/200801/2547.php|url-status=live}}</ref>[[File:Ghana_national_football_team_(Black_Stars)_badge_and_national_anthem.jpg|thumb|Badge and anthem]]

Between 1990 and 2006 the Ghana national team used the kit in the colours of the national flag of Ghana, with gold, green and red used, as in the team's [[Crest (heraldry)|crest]] and also known as the [[Pan-African colours]]. The gold with green and red kit concept and design was used in the 60s and 70s, and designed with gold and green vertical stripes and red shoulders. An all black second kit was introduced in 2008 and in 2015, Black Stars' gold-red-green coloured kit and all black coloured kit is to be reassigned to the position of 1st and 2nd kits following the induction of a brown with blue and gold coloured Black Stars 3rd kit in 2012.<ref name="Black Stars 3rd Kit"/><ref name="Black Stars To Play State Envoy In Friendly This Afternoon"/>

The team's kit for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]] was ranked as the best kit of the tournament by [[BuzzFeed]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://graphic.com.gh/sports/sports-news/24825-brazil-204-ghana-s-jersey-s-ranked-the-best.html|location=Accra, Ghana|title=Brazil 2014: Ghana's jersey ranked the best (GFA)|date=10 June 2014|access-date=28 September 2014|archive-date=13 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140613102707/http://graphic.com.gh/sports/sports-news/24825-brazil-204-ghana-s-jersey-s-ranked-the-best.html|url-status=live|newspaper=[[Daily Graphic]]}}</ref>
