===Organisation and finance===
The Black Stars had no official head because of "corrupt" practices<ref>{{Cite web |date=2018-06-07 |title=Ghana Football Association dissolved after bribery allegations |url=https://www.africanews.com/2018/06/07/ghana-football-association-dissolved-after-bribery-allegations/ |access-date=2023-06-16 |website=Africanews |language=en |archive-date=16 June 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230616193619/https://www.africanews.com/2018/06/07/ghana-football-association-dissolved-after-bribery-allegations/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2020-09-18 |title=Number 12: Ghana FA begins charging implicated individuals of famous Anas corruption expose |url=https://www.goal.com/en-gh/news/number-12-ghana-fa-begins-charging-implicated-individuals-of-famous-anas-corruption-expose/otg5f6xf7tch1q47ruo6s8qq0 |access-date=2023-06-16 |website=Goal |language=en-GH |archive-date=16 June 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230616193615/https://www.goal.com/en-gh/news/number-12-ghana-fa-begins-charging-implicated-individuals-of-famous-anas-corruption-expose/otg5f6xf7tch1q47ruo6s8qq0 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=2018-06-07 |title=Ghana dissolves football association after cash gifts scandal |language=en-GB |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-44406535 |access-date=2023-06-16 |archive-date=16 June 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230616193618/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-44406535 |url-status=live }}</ref> by the then president, [[Kwesi Nyantakyi]]<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.ghanafa.org/pages/gfa/201409/9827.php | title= National team reforms underway&nbsp;– GFA President | publisher= [[Ghana Football Association]] | date= 3 September 2014 | access-date= 28 September 2014 | archive-date= 5 September 2014 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140905231102/http://ghanafa.org/pages/gfa/201409/9827.php | url-status= live }}</ref> and vice-president George Afriyie,<ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.ghanafa.org/pages/gfa/201209/7577.php | title= Crentsil elected GFA Vice President | work= ghanafa.org | publisher= [[Ghana Football Association]] | date= 25 September 2012 | access-date= 28 September 2014 | archive-date= 11 December 2014 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141211012041/http://www.ghanafa.org/pages/gfa/201209/7577.php | url-status= live }}</ref> with Frank Davis as [[director of football]], and Edward Bawa as treasurer.<ref name="Kwesi Nyantakyi">{{cite news |url=http://thechronicle.com.gh/kwesi-nyantakyi-clinches-top-caf-post/ |title=Kwesi Nyantakyi clinches top Caf post |work=[[The Ghanaian Chronicle]] |access-date=19 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105231841/http://thechronicle.com.gh/kwesi-nyantakyi-clinches-top-caf-post/ |archive-date=5 November 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The Ghana Football Association (GFA) signed a [[Renminbi|CN¥]]92.2 million (US$15 million) deal with Ghanaian state-run [[oil and gas exploration]] corporation, [[Ghana National Petroleum Corporation]] (GNPC), to [[Sponsor (commercial)|sponsor]] the Black Stars and the renewable contract saw the oil and gas exploration corporation become the global headline sponsor of the Black Stars, with a yearly Black Stars player salary wage bill,<ref>{{cite news | date=15 January 2013 | url=http://sports.myjoyonline.com/pages/news/201301/100633.php | title=GNPC hails Black Stars | work=myjoyonline.com | access-date=29 May 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130131104806/http://sports.myjoyonline.com/pages/news/201301/100633.php | archive-date=31 January 2013 | url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | date=15 January 2013 | url=http://www.ghana.gov.gh/index.php/news/sports/afcon-2013/19485-gnpc-hails-black-stars- | title=GNPC hails Black Stars | work=ghana.gov.gh | access-date=29 May 2013 | archive-date=4 March 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304032542/http://www.ghana.gov.gh/index.php/news/sports/afcon-2013/19485-gnpc-hails-black-stars- | url-status=live }}</ref> following the [[gold mining]] corporations [[Ashanti Goldfields Corporation]] and Goldfields Ghana Limited (GGL), which had been sponsoring the Black Stars since 2005.

On 28 August 2013, Ghana Football Association (GFA) launched a [[TV channel]] and named [[GFA TV]]. The channel has the [[exclusive right]]s to broadcast all the Black Stars' matches.<ref name="Ghana Football Association launches GFA TV">{{cite news | url= http://allsports.com.gh/2013/08/27/ghana-football-association-launches-gfa-tv/ | title= Ghana Football Association launches GFA TV | work= allsports.com.gh | access-date= 19 September 2013 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130930035148/http://allsports.com.gh/2013/08/27/ghana-football-association-launches-gfa-tv/ | archive-date= 30 September 2013 | url-status= dead }}</ref> In November 2013, the Black Stars signed a 2013–2015 CN¥30.6 million (US$5 million) and an additional [[Classified information|classified]] multi-million [[private bank]] sponsorship deal with the Ghanaian state-run [[private banking]] institution [[UniBank]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/africa/2013-11/08/c_132869165.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131208010536/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/africa/2013-11/08/c_132869165.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=8 December 2013| title= Ghana's national team gets sponsorship |author=Alex Osei-Boateng|work= news.xinhuanet.com | agency=[[Xinhua News Agency]] | access-date=21 November 2013}}</ref>

===Supporters===
[[File:ACON_2015_GHA_GUI_(16512008192).jpg|thumb|261x261px|Ghanaian supporters at the 2015 AFCON match between Ghana and Guinea]]
The Black Stars maintain an average stadium match attendance of over 60,000, with 84,017 watching the [[2010 FIFA World Cup knockout stage#Uruguay vs Ghana|2010 FIFA World Cup quarter-final]] against [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]].<ref name="Ghana 1&nbsp;– 1 Uruguay">{{cite web | date=2 July 2010 |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/southafrica2010/matches/round=249718/match=300061508/report.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110205135019/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/southafrica2010/matches/round=249718/match=300061508/report.html|url-status=
dead|archive-date=5 February 2011| title=Ghana 1&nbsp;– 1 Uruguay (1:1 a.e.t. (1:1, 0:1) 4:2 PSO)|work=[[FIFA]] | access-date=15 September 2013}}</ref> Ghana's match against [[England national football team|England]] on 29 March 2011 had the largest away following for any association football national team since the re-opening of [[Wembley Stadium]] in 2007.<ref name="Tickets For Ghana And England Maiden International Friendly Sold Out" /> The match was watched by 700 million people around the world.<ref name="Tickets For Ghana And England Maiden International Friendly Sold Out" />

Following the team's appearances at the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006]] and [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010 World Cup]] tournaments, they were greeted by some hundred avid fans dancing and singing at [[Accra International Airport]] in Accra.<ref name="Ghana gives Black Stars heroes' welcome after World Cup">{{cite news |date=6 July 2010 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10508969 |title=Ghana gives Black Stars heroes' welcome after World Cup |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=15 September 2013 |archive-date=20 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130620194125/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10508969 |url-status=live }}</ref>

===Rivalries===
{{main|Jollof derby}}

[[File:Sulley.jpg|thumb|291x291px|Ghana against [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]] in the [[2008 Africa Cup of Nations#Quarter-finals|2008 Africa Cup of Nations quarter-final]]]]
Ghana is rivals with [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]]. The "Battle of Supremacy on the [[Gulf of Guinea]]" is between two of the "most successful teams on the African continent".<ref name="Rivals herald African awakening (Ghana vs Nigeria)">{{cite web|work = fifa.com|publisher=[[FIFA]]|title=Rivals herald African awakening (Ghana vs Nigeria)|url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/matches/qualifiers/match=1517/index.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130305011657/http://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/matches/qualifiers/match=1517/index.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=5 March 2013|access-date =12 September 2013}}</ref> The proximity of the two countries to each other, a dispute between the different association football competitions and [[Ghana–Nigeria relations|wider diplomatic competition for influence]] across West Africa add to this rivalry.<ref name="Rivals herald African awakening (Ghana vs Nigeria)" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-54088878|title=Letter from Africa: Behind Ghana and Nigeria's love-hate affair|work=BBC News|date=12 September 2020|access-date=13 September 2020|archive-date=13 September 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200913210702/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-54088878|url-status=live}}</ref> The match between these two countries is called the [[Jollof derby]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=VAR, Fun and Disappointment: Ghana and Nigeria 'jollof derby' leaves fans asking for more |url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/var-fun-and-disappointment-ghana-and-nigeria-jollof-derby-leaves-/blt3e99155ae19618b2 |access-date=2022-03-30 |website=Goal |archive-date=31 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220331171523/https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/var-fun-and-disappointment-ghana-and-nigeria-jollof-derby-leaves-/blt3e99155ae19618b2 |url-status=live }}</ref>

===Media and arts===
Match schedules are broadcast in English as in the case of inter-continental matches and in [[Akan people|Akan]] nationally by Adom TV, PeaceFM, AdomFM and HappyFM. During the [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification|scheduled qualification]] for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014 World Cup]] national broadcaster [[GTV (Ghana)|GTV]], a sub-division of the [[Ghana Broadcasting Corporation]] (GBC), broadcast to the Ghanaian public home qualifiers with away qualifiers broadcast by the satellite television broadcasting corporation [[Viasat 1]]. The friendly match against [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]] in August 2013 was televised by Viasat 1 and the qualifiers for the [[2015 Africa Cup of Nations]] and the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018 Inter-Continental Championships]] are scheduled for public broadcast by the corporations [[GFA TV]], [[Ghana Broadcasting Corporation|GBC]] and [[Viasat 1]].<ref>{{cite news | title = GTV Sports+ to telecast live premier league matches | work = liquidsportsghana.com | date = 29 September 2012 | access-date = 14 September 2013 | url = http://www.liquidsportsghana.com/?p=football&id=626 | archive-date = 29 October 2013 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131029200147/http://www.liquidsportsghana.com/?p=football&id=626 | url-status = live }}</ref>

Products including books, documentary films, [[Azonto|Azonto dances]] and songs have been made in the name of the team. These may be intended with commercial motives and are focused on previous and future [[FIFA World Cup|World Cups]] or [[Africa Cup of Nations]] tournaments.

* Books: books have been published on the team's history and participation in tournaments. These include ''Ghana, The Rediscovered Soccer Might: Watch Out World!'',<ref>{{cite book |last1= Bonna |first1= Okyere |title= Ghana, The Rediscovered Soccer Might: Watch Out World! |year= 2008 |publisher= [[AuthorHouse]] |location= Bloomington, Indiana}}</ref> about the history and performance of the Black Stars and association football [[National sports team|national teams]] that the Black Stars have played against, and ''The Black Stars of Ghana'' by Alan Whelan;<ref>{{cite book |last= Whelan |first= Alan |title=The Black Stars of Ghana|year= 2012 |publisher= Inkstand Press |isbn = 978-0-9572248-0-3}}</ref> about Black Stars commencing their progress through the final rounds of the 2010 World Cup and into the quarter-finals.
* Documentary films: In 2010 Miracle Films Ghana Limited showcased a vintage documentary film picture, ''Kwame Nkrumah & Ghana's Black Stars'', about Osagyefo [[Kwame Nkrumah]] "Africa's man of the 2nd millennium" and "[[Pan-African]] pioneer",<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/people/highlights/000914_nkrumah.shtml|title= Kwame Nkrumah's Vision of Africa|work= [[BBC World Service]]|date= 14 September 2000|access-date= 16 September 2013|archive-date= 25 July 2013|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130725113031/http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/people/highlights/000914_nkrumah.shtml|url-status= live}}</ref> who invested energy into making Ghana's association football national team&nbsp;– the Black Stars&nbsp;– a force in African soccer.<ref name="Kwame Nkrumah & Ghana's Black Stars (2010)">{{cite web |title=Kwame Nkrumah & Ghana's Black Stars (2010) |url=http://www.footysphere.com/post/879393803/nkrumah-black-stars-ghana |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140112000000/http://www.footysphere.com/post/879393803/nkrumah-black-stars-ghana |archive-date=12 January 2014 |access-date=16 September 2013}}</ref>
* Nickname: The [[Black Star Line]], a [[shipping industry]] line [[Corporation|incorporated]] by the founder of the [[Back-to-Africa movement]], [[civil rights movement]] leader [[Marcus Garvey]] and the organiser of the [[Universal Negro Improvement Association and African Communities League]] (UNIA) from 1919 to 1922, gives the Ghana team its nicknames, the Black Stars of West Africa and the Black Stars of Africa.<ref name="Kwame Nkrumah & Ghana's Black Stars (2010)"/>
* Dances: upon the Black Stars scoring against opposition teams, dance forms of the Ghanaian [[Azonto]] were performed by Black Stars players in their [[goal celebration]]s in match victories at the 2010 World Cup and in 2013, an elite dance version of the Ghanaian Azonto named; "({{langx|ak|Mmonko}})" (''shrimp''), was established and showcased at the [[2013 Africa Cup of Nations]] by the Black Stars players.<ref>{{cite web |title= Ghana's Black Stars football team to debut new celebration dance at AFCON 2013 |work= missgo2girl.com |date= 20 January 2013 |access-date= 16 September 2013 |url= http://www.missgo2girl.com/ghanas-black-star-football-team-to-debut-new-celebration-dance-at-afcon-2013/ |archive-date= 22 February 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140222194449/http://missgo2girl.com/ghanas-black-star-football-team-to-debut-new-celebration-dance-at-afcon-2013/ |url-status= live }}</ref> Black Stars [[goal celebration]]s in match victories at the 2014 World Cup and upon scoring against opposition teams, are to establish and showcase [[Alkayida]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ghanasportsonline.com/index.php/local-football-news/item/1522-ghana-striker-asamoah-gyan-to-launch-alkayida-dance-at-brazil-world-cup|title=Ghana Striker Asamoah Gyan To Launch Alkayida Dance at Brazil World Cup|work=ghanasportsonline.com|date=31 March 2014|access-date=27 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408224122/http://ghanasportsonline.com/index.php/local-football-news/item/1522-ghana-striker-asamoah-gyan-to-launch-alkayida-dance-at-brazil-world-cup|archive-date=8 April 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>
* Songs: On occasions of past [[FIFA World Cup|World Cups]] or [[Africa Cup of Nations|African Championships]], a number of musicians with music producers created [[hiplife]] [[football song]]s which were composed in the [[Akan language]]&nbsp;– the 2006 World Cup song, "{{langx|ak|Tuntum Nsorom Ye Ko Yen Anim}}", (Black Stars, We are moving forward) [[Musical composition|musical composed]] by the [[Musicians Union of Ghana]], is to motivate the Black Stars to perform creditably in its quest for the capturing of the World Cup trophy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.modernghana.com/mobile/87331/2/black-stars-victory-song-launched.html |title=Black Stars victory song launched |work=modernghana.com |date=2 October 2005 |access-date=16 September 2013 |archive-date=17 October 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017220313/http://m.modernghana.com/mobile/87331/2/black-stars-victory-song-launched.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Black Stars' [[Captain (association football)|captain]] and top-goalscorer [[Asamoah Gyan]] recorded and released a [[Hiplife]] song with '[[Castro de Destroyer|Castro The Destroyer]]', where he features under the alias 'Baby Jet'. The song is entitled "African Girls" and is sung in the Akan language and was launched onto the Ghanaian screens, continental West Africa screens and onto the [[Sub-Saharan Africa]] screens. The music video shows the "Asamoah Gyan Dance" [[goal celebration]] which he demonstrated at the 2010 World Cup. The song "African Girls" won an award at the Ghana Music Awards in 2011. The 2010 World Cup song, "Ghana Black Stars (Official Song 2010 World Cup)" composed by Ghanaian hiplife music group "Kings and Queens Entertainment" approved by the [[Ghana Football Association]] (GFA) as GFA has indicated that the Black Stars are a protected brand.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-12-01 |title=How music became embedded in Ghanaian football fan culture |url=https://www.inkl.com/news/how-music-became-embedded-in-ghanaian-football-fan-culture |access-date=2024-12-28 |website=inkl |language=en}}</ref>

